{{define "30-collaboration.tmpl"}}
{{with .Collaboration}}
<section class="narrative">
  <h2>Collaboration</h2>

  {{with .PullRequests}}
  <div class="metric-story">
    <h3>Pull requests</h3>
    <div class="stats">
      <div class="stat"><span class="n">{{.Authored}}</span><span class="muted">authored</span></div>
      <div class="stat"><span class="n">{{.Merged}}</span><span class="muted">merged</span></div>
    </div>
    <p>
      {{if ge .Merged 30}}
      A high volume of merged pull requests indicates sustained, steady contribution
      across the coverage window.
      {{else if ge .Merged 10}}
      A moderate number of merged pull requests shows consistent delivery over the period.
      {{else}}
      Pull request volume was low over this period, which may reflect focused work on
      long-running branches, non-PR workflows, or a quieter window.
      {{end}}
    </p>
    <p class="muted limit">
      <strong>Limit:</strong> volume alone says nothing about the size or quality of the work.
      A developer who ships many small, well-scoped changes and one who ships a single
      multi-thousand-line PR both show up here as a count. Use this number as orientation,
      not as a measure of output.
    </p>
  </div>
  {{end}}

  {{with .ReviewsGiven}}
  <div class="metric-story">
    <h3>Reviews given</h3>
    <div class="stats">
      <div class="stat"><span class="n">{{.Total}}</span><span class="muted">total reviews</span></div>
      <div class="stat"><span class="n">{{.Approvals}}</span><span class="muted">approvals</span></div>
      <div class="stat"><span class="n">{{.ChangesRequested}}</span><span class="muted">changes requested</span></div>
    </div>
    <p>
      {{if ge .Total 40}}
      This developer is a very active reviewer, investing significant time in teammates&rsquo; work.
      {{else if ge .Total 15}}
      Reviews given at a healthy cadence, showing regular engagement with the team&rsquo;s output.
      {{else if ge .Total 1}}
      Some review participation in the period. Context matters: some roles or team sizes
      naturally produce fewer review opportunities.
      {{else}}
      No reviews recorded. This may reflect a role that does not involve peer review,
      or a period focused entirely on authoring.
      {{end}}
    </p>
    <p class="muted limit">
      <strong>Limit:</strong> review counts do not capture review depth &mdash; a one-word
      &ldquo;LGTM&rdquo; and a detailed structural critique look identical here.
      The changes-requested count is a rough proxy for engagement, not a quality judgement.
    </p>
  </div>
  {{end}}

  {{with .ReviewComments}}
  <div class="metric-story">
    <h3>Review comments</h3>
    <div class="stats">
      <div class="stat"><span class="n">{{.Written}}</span><span class="muted">written</span></div>
      <div class="stat"><span class="n">{{.Received}}</span><span class="muted">received</span></div>
    </div>
    <p>
      Comment counts show the texture of the code-review dialogue: how much inline
      feedback this developer gives and receives. A higher written count alongside a
      higher received count often signals active mutual engagement.
    </p>
    <p class="muted limit">
      <strong>Limit:</strong> comment counts are extremely noisy. A single heated thread
      can inflate the number; a highly skilled reviewer who spots the root issue in one
      sentence will show a low count. Treat this as a rough signal only.
    </p>
  </div>
  {{end}}

  {{with .TimeToMerge}}
  <div class="metric-story">
    <h3>Time to merge</h3>
    <div class="stats">
      <div class="stat"><span class="n">{{hours .MedianHours}}h</span><span class="muted">median</span></div>
      <div class="stat"><span class="n">{{.Count}}</span><span class="muted">merged PRs</span></div>
    </div>
    <p>
      {{if le .MedianHours 24.0}}
      Pull requests merged quickly on the median, suggesting lightweight scoping,
      an active review culture, or both.
      {{else if le .MedianHours 72.0}}
      Median merge time is moderate &mdash; typical for teams that run async review
      cycles or require multiple approvals.
      {{else}}
      Pull requests take longer to close on the median. This can reflect large,
      careful changes, slower review availability, or approval-gate requirements.
      {{end}}
    </p>
    <p class="muted limit">
      <strong>Limit:</strong> this measures elapsed wall-clock time, not working time.
      Weekend drafts, long-running feature branches opened early, or approval-gate
      automation all inflate the number without indicating a problem.
    </p>
  </div>
  {{end}}

  {{with .TimeToFirstReview}}
  <div class="metric-story">
    <h3>Time to first review</h3>
    <div class="stats">
      <div class="stat"><span class="n">{{hours .MedianHours}}h</span><span class="muted">median</span></div>
      <div class="stat"><span class="n">{{.Count}}</span><span class="muted">PRs reviewed</span></div>
    </div>
    <p>
      How long, on the median, before a teammate picked up this developer&rsquo;s
      pull request and left a first review. Short times suggest an attentive team or
      proactive review culture; longer times can simply reflect cross-timezone work or
      a small team.
    </p>
    <p class="muted limit">
      <strong>Limit:</strong> PRs that were never reviewed are excluded from this
      calculation. If many PRs go unreviewed, the median understates the typical wait.
    </p>
  </div>
  {{end}}

  {{with .Rework}}
  <div class="metric-story">
    <h3>Rework rate</h3>
    <div class="stats">
      <div class="stat"><span class="n">{{percent .Share}}</span><span class="muted">of reviewed PRs</span></div>
      <div class="stat"><span class="n">{{.ReworkedPRs}} of {{.ReviewedPRs}}</span><span class="muted">reviewed</span></div>
    </div>
    <p>
      The share of this developer&rsquo;s reviewed pull requests where at least one
      reviewer requested changes before approval.
      {{if le .Share 0.15}}
      A low rework rate can reflect well-scoped, polished submissions &mdash; or reviewers
      who rarely request changes. Both are plausible.
      {{else if le .Share 0.40}}
      A moderate rework rate is common and healthy: it shows that reviewers are
      engaged and that the author responds to feedback.
      {{else}}
      A higher rework rate is worth discussing with the developer. It may indicate
      misaligned expectations, scope creep, or simply that reviewers on this team are
      thorough and standards are high.
      {{end}}
    </p>
    <p class="muted limit">
      <strong>Limit:</strong> some rework is normal and desirable &mdash; it means the
      review process is working. This metric cannot distinguish between a developer
      who iterates quickly on feedback and one who struggles. The denominator is
      reviewed PRs only; unreviewed PRs are excluded.
    </p>
  </div>
  {{end}}

</section>
{{end}}
{{end}}
